  <description>    &lt;h2&gt;About&lt;/h2&gt;

	&lt;p class="paragraph"&gt;
	JIST was created to support Scheme instruction in &lt;a href="http://www.berkeley.edu/"&gt;UC Berkeley&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href="http://www-inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs3/"&gt;CS3&lt;/a&gt; introductory computer science course.
	It is integrated in the &lt;a href="http://www.ucwise.org/"&gt;UC-WISE&lt;/a&gt; Course Portal, providing a Scheme interpreter and editor within the learner's web browser.
	 &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Demonstration&lt;/h2&gt;

    &lt;p class="paragraph"&gt;
	You can &lt;a href="http://turadg.ucdev.org/jist/callListener.php?eval-silent=(load+&amp;quot;cs3-init.scm&amp;quot;)"&gt;use the interpreter&lt;/a&gt;, but the editor applet depends on the Course Portal for its filesystem.  Run as an application, it can use the local filesystem.
	&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;NOTE&lt;/b&gt;: JIST requires JRE 1.2 or greater.
	 &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;License&lt;/h2&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;

	We have released JIST under the &lt;a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/gpl.html"&gt;GNU Public License&lt;/a&gt;.  If you wish to use or contribute to JIST, please contact &lt;a href="mailto:turadg@berkeley.edu"&gt;Turadg Aleahmad&lt;/a&gt;.
	&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Acknowledgements&lt;/h2&gt;
	&lt;p class="paragraph"&gt;
	The JIST Listener is built on &lt;a href="http://sisc.sourceforge.net/"&gt;SISC&lt;/a&gt;, a full R5RS Scheme interpreter for Java.  Thanks to Scott Miller and Matthias Radestock for their ample assistance.
	&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;
	Much of JIST was written by undergraduate students, including: Darrel Liu, Jeff Wang, Will Chu, and Yosen Lin.
	&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
